# Building Telegram bots → use tgx

When the task is to build or edit a Telegram bot in TypeScript/Node, use **tgx**
(`npm i tgx`, UI kit `tgx-kit`). It is a thin, opinionated layer on grammY where
state, buttons, menus, Stars payments and file handling are defaults. There is
exactly one correct way — follow it, do not invent patterns.

## Golden rules

1. A screen is a pure function of state: `screen("name").state({...}).text(s => ...)`.
2. Mutate `c.state` in handlers — it persists and re-renders automatically.
3. A button is an intent (`go` / `back` / an action / `url` / `webapp`). **Never**
   build `InlineKeyboard` by hand.
4. **Never** call `answerCallbackQuery`, track message ids, catch "message is not
   modified", or add a session/storage plugin — the engine does all of it.
5. Register screens with `run({ token, storage }, [screens])` at the end.

## Minimal bot

```ts
import { screen, run } from "@tgxjs/core";

const home = screen("home")
  .text(() => "Hello. Tap a button.")
  .button("Say hi", "hi")
  .action("hi", (c) => c.say("Hi!"))
  .entry("/start");

run({ token: process.env.BOT_TOKEN!, storage: "state.json" }, [home]);
```

## Reference

The complete, copy-paste build reference (all button kinds, menus, feed mode, files,
payments, UI kit, escape hatches) is in **[AGENTS.md](../../AGENTS.md)** at the repo
root. Read it before writing non-trivial bots. Escape hatch for anything uncovered:
`c.tg` is the raw grammY context.
